22-point victory. Not Connecticut's Geno Auriemma.
article.headline: Strother, Taurasi lead Huskies to victory
article.linkText: Auriemma unhappy despite No. 2 UConn's win vs. Holy Cross
article.story:
WORCESTER, Mass. -- Most coaches would be satisfied with a
22-point victory. Not Connecticut's Geno Auriemma.

	   The Huskies' coach saw plenty of room for improvement after Ann
Strother scored 18 points, and combined with Diana Taurasi to key a
decisive second-half run that led (No. 2 ESPN/USA Today, No. 3 AP) UConn over Holy Cross 68-46
Thursday night.

	   "If you play teams that don't have as much talent, you have to
be more dominant,'' Auriemma said. "We have a laid back approach
and I think it may catch up to us.

	   "It's careless. And this hasn't been part of Connecticut
basketball. Give Holy Cross credit, but there should be a bigger
gap between us and them.''

	   Taurasi, held to four points in the first half, finished with 14
for the Huskies (6-0), who have won 45 straight games. Katie
O'Keefe scored 23 points to lead Holy Cross (2-3).

	   Connecticut needs more than Strother and Taurasi to win,
Auriemma said.

	   Strother is "not your typical freshman who worries about making
mistakes or missing a shot,'' he said. "She's always looking for
the next play to make. She's an impact player already.''

	   "There are times when Diana's or Ann's talents are carrying us,
but others have to fill up the stat sheet. You can't just gave two
players.''

	   The Crusaders trailed 27-25 at halftime, but O'Keefe put Holy
Cross ahead 32-29 with a 3-pointer early in the second half. But
Strother and Taurasi combined for nine points in a 14-0 run by the
defending NCAA champions.

	   "Overall our defense is what got us going in the second half,''
Strother said. "We've struggled because we've had a lack of
discipline on both offense and defense. In the first half we just
didn't take care of the ball.''

	   Holy Cross, the defending Patriot League champions, was looking
for its first win over UConn since 1986.

	   "Obviously, a lot of people thought we'd get blown out, but we
hung in there,'' Holy Cross coach Bill Gibbons said. "Our kids
gave it their blood and guts and they believed we could win.''

	   O'Keefe scored seven points in the game's first 10 minutes. The
Crusaders, aided by four UConn turnovers, took an 11-10 lead with
11:04 left after O'Keefe sank one of two free throws.

	   "We used the shot clock and executed superbly in the first
half, but it's hard to hold the ball against a team that plays so
hard, so aggressively,'' Gibbons said.

	   Taurasi and Jessica Moore had two baskets apiece as the Huskies
took a 17-14 lead with 8:46 left in the half.

	   After Liz O'Connor nailed a 3-point field goal to tie the game,
Maria Conlon answered with a 3-pointer to give UConn a 20-17 lead.
Conlon replaced starter Ashley Battle, who sustained an ankle
injury in the first half.

	   A putback by Nicole Wolff gave UConn a 25-19 lead with four
minutes left. But Holy Cross rallied, as O'Keefe hit a pair of
baskets, cutting the lead to two points at halftime.

	   Taurasi took her coach's harsh words in stride.

	   "He's testing us, and it's not a matter of Xs and Os but our
character,'' she said. "He's right to put the challenge on us.
It's either fold or grow up.''
